The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Heat wave claims seven
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      Heat wave claims seven
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Bhubaneswar, April 14: The unabated heat wave in the state claimed at least seven lives, as conditions worsened with the mercury showing no signs of coming down.        
	According to sources in the disaster management control room, seven persons including three women, died of sunstroke this month.        
	While two persons have fallen victim to the heat wave in Angul and Ganjam districts, one casualty each was reported from Balasore, Jajpur and Mayurbhanj districts.        
	Allegations of sunstroke deaths have reached the disaster management department, out of which seven were confirmed following joint inquiry by health and disaster management departments. Seven more deaths were found to be because of other reasons. Rest of the reports was under investigation, said a senior official in the disaster management department.        
	Till yesterday, 42 reports of deaths were received and three more reached today, said the official.        
	Severe heat wave was sweeping across the state with the mercury hovering above 40 degrees Celsius in at least 14 places.        
	The highest  45.5 degrees Celsius  was recorded at Sambalpur, followed by Bolangir and Hirakud (44.9), Jharsuguda (44.6) and Sundargarh (44). Bhubaneswar recorded 40.5 degrees Celsius today.        
	The heat wave conditions would prevail over some parts of the state during the next 48 hours, Met officials said.                                                                                                                                                          
